\@writefile{lot}{\contentsline {table}{\numberline {V}{\ignorespaces Is the int8 collapse caused by our student, or by its architecture? The two MobileNetV3-Small arms are replicated over five training seeds on a fixed split with matched training budgets, so only the loss differs; values are mean~$\pm $~SD over seeds, at a fixed calibration seed. The ResNet50 teacher is a single checkpoint, replicated instead over five calibration draws. All models are quantized through the identical PT2E path (per-channel weights, $1{,}024$ calibration images) and evaluated on the Cassava single-split test set. The int8 standard deviations are large by nature, not by accident: see the text on calibration noise.}}{5}{table.5}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{tab:quant-arch}{{V}{5}{Is the int8 collapse caused by our student, or by its architecture? The two MobileNetV3-Small arms are replicated over five training seeds on a fixed split with matched training budgets, so only the loss differs; values are mean~$\pm $~SD over seeds, at a fixed calibration seed. The ResNet50 teacher is a single checkpoint, replicated instead over five calibration draws. All models are quantized through the identical PT2E path (per-channel weights, $1{,}024$ calibration images) and evaluated on the Cassava single-split test set. The int8 standard deviations are large by nature, not by accident: see the text on calibration noise}{table.5}{}}
